### Context API

Context provides a way to pass data through the component tree without manually passing props at every level. It is designed for global or widely-shared data.

---

### Creating Context

```jsx
import { createContext } from 'react';

const ThemeContext = createContext('light');
```

### Provider Component

```jsx
function ThemeProvider({ children }) {
  const [theme, setTheme] = useState('light');

  const toggleTheme = () => {
    setTheme(prev => prev === 'light' ? 'dark' : 'light');
  };

  return (
    <ThemeContext.Provider value={{ theme, toggleTheme }}>
      {children}
    </ThemeContext.Provider>
  );
}
```

### Context and Performance

| Issue | Solution |
|-------|----------|
| All consumers re-render on any value change | Split contexts by concern |
| Deep tree of providers | Compose providers into a single wrapper |
| Frequent updates | Use memoization or separate fast-changing values |

### Composing Providers

```jsx
function AppProviders({ children }) {
  return (
    <ThemeProvider>
      <AuthProvider>
        <LanguageProvider>
          {children}
        </LanguageProvider>
      </AuthProvider>
    </ThemeProvider>
  );
}
```

### When to Use Context

| Good for Context | Not good for Context |
|-----------------|---------------------|
| Theme (light/dark) | Frequently updating data |
| User authentication | High-frequency real-time data |
| Locale/language | Server state (use TanStack Query) |
| Feature flags | Form state (keep local) |

> **Key Point:** Context is NOT a replacement for state management libraries. It solves prop drilling for data that is truly global. Overusing context leads to unnecessary re-renders and performance issues.

